1
00:01:51,612 --> 00:01:55,907
Company .. halt!

2
00:03:05,566 --> 00:03:07,519
Good morning.
─ Good morning.

3
00:03:09,776 --> 00:03:12,499
???? ????

4
00:03:13,268 --> 00:03:13,822
Is someone ill?

5
00:03:13,942 --> 00:03:15,718
For the Captain ma'am.
He can't leave the bridge.

6
00:03:16,045 --> 00:03:17,920
Beautiful soup. Tomato soup.

7
00:03:21,497 --> 00:03:24,393
Mrs Sorenson has no life-jacket.
─ Mrs Sorenson has no life-jacket?

8
00:03:24,513 --> 00:03:25,914
Shhh. No life-jacket.

9
00:03:26,327 --> 00:03:28,056
Did you hear that Mr Payton?

10
00:03:29,404 --> 00:03:31,332
Mrs Sorenson has no life-jacket.
─ Who?

11
00:03:31,623 --> 00:03:32,956
Mrs Sorenson.

12
00:03:33,325 --> 00:03:35,654
My dear, haven't you forgotten
your life-jacket?

13
00:03:35,953 --> 00:03:36,709
Hardly.

14
00:03:36,918 --> 00:03:39,647
Mrs Sorenson, I think you've forgotten
your life-jacket.

15
00:03:40,275 --> 00:03:42,386
Thank you Mr Skold,
but I prefer not to wear it.

16
00:03:43,113 --> 00:03:45,424
Captain's orders Mrs Sorenson.
─ Really?

17
00:03:50,354 --> 00:03:51,991
Mr Hansen.
─ Sir?

18
00:03:52,628 --> 00:03:55,012
Put another lookout on the starboard bow.
─ Yes sir.

19
00:04:01,330 --> 00:04:04,451
Ahoy there! Put another
lookout to starboard.

20
00:04:05,388 --> 00:04:06,907
Jump to it.

21
00:04:11,561 --> 00:04:14,782
I have to report sir, that Mrs Sorensen
refuses to put on her life-jacket.

22
00:04:15,301 --> 00:04:18,285
Make her put it on.
─ I've tried sir, but she won't.

23
00:04:24,419 --> 00:04:25,980
Mr Hansen.
─ Sir?

24
00:04:26,189 --> 00:04:28,841
Ask Mrs Sorensen to see me in my cabin.
─ Yes, sir.

25
00:04:35,358 --> 00:04:37,692
When I saw her come aboard I
knew we were in for trouble.

26
00:04:38,027 --> 00:04:39,041
Did you sir?

27
00:04:41,096 --> 00:04:42,818
Not that I don't like them that way.

28
00:04:43,737 --> 00:04:45,093
Not in peacetime, sir.

29
00:04:47,520 --> 00:04:49,059
And ashore.

30
00:05:16,907 --> 00:05:18,908
Come in Mrs Sorenson.

31
00:05:25,424 --> 00:05:26,589
You wanted to see me Captain?

32
00:05:26,898 --> 00:05:29,245
What is your objection to wearing
a life-jacket?

33
00:05:30,155 --> 00:05:31,592
Apparently the same as yours.

34
00:05:37,634 --> 00:05:39,709
Mrs Sorenson, have you ever
been put in irons?

35
00:05:40,273 --> 00:05:40,665
No.

36
00:05:40,921 --> 00:05:43,673
You will find it much more uncomfortable
than wearing a life-jacket.

37
00:05:44,023 --> 00:05:46,262
You can't put me in irons because
I refuse to wear a life-jacket.

38
00:05:46,763 --> 00:05:48,240
You are mistaken Mrs Sorenson.

39
00:05:48,799 --> 00:05:50,856
I am the captain of this ship and
you are a passenger.

40
00:05:50,976 --> 00:05:53,457
My job is to give orders,
and yours is to obey them.

41
00:05:54,514 --> 00:05:58,021
I am responsible for the safety of every
person in my ship and I am determined ..

42
00:05:58,273 --> 00:06:01,526
Take my passengers safely to the port
for which they have bought their tickets.

43
00:06:01,858 --> 00:06:03,539
Whether you like it or not!

44
00:06:07,241 --> 00:06:08,256
Steward!

45
00:06:12,144 --> 00:06:14,153
You're not really going to
put me in irons?

46
00:06:17,960 --> 00:06:18,462
Sir?

47
00:06:18,669 --> 00:06:21,287
Fetch Mrs Sorenson's life-jacket.
─ Aye aye, sir.

48
00:06:23,719 --> 00:06:26,006
In 48 hours you will be
ashore at Copenhagen.

49
00:06:27,275 --> 00:06:28,877
Where you can wear whatever you like.

50
00:06:29,389 --> 00:06:31,800
But while you are on my ship,
you will obey my orders.

51
00:06:32,592 --> 00:06:33,410
Sir!

52
00:06:34,138 --> 00:06:35,430
You're wanted on the bridge, sir.

53
00:06:48,451 --> 00:06:49,943
A British patrol boat.

54
00:06:58,258 --> 00:07:01,824
We .. wish .. to .. speak .. with .. you.

55
00:07:03,425 --> 00:07:04,872
We wish to speak with you.

56
00:07:05,636 --> 00:07:07,401
As if we weren't late enough already.

57
00:07:08,048 --> 00:07:11,578
They want to take us into a Control Port
and hold us there for days or weeks.

58
00:07:11,980 --> 00:07:13,270
Better than meeting a U-Boat anyway sir.

59
00:07:13,563 --> 00:07:15,418
Oh they say U-Boat Commanders
are very polite.

60
00:07:15,663 --> 00:07:18,843
Yes .. afterwards.

61
00:07:23,395 --> 00:07:25,097
She looks pretty fast, sir.

62
00:07:36,674 --> 00:07:39,213
One round, blank .. load.

63
00:07:43,006 --> 00:07:44,689
They are signaling again, sir.

64
00:07:47,703 --> 00:07:49,950
Heave to immediately.

65
00:07:52,315 --> 00:07:53,489
Let them come and get me.

66
00:07:53,771 --> 00:07:55,504
Fire!

67
00:09:30,182 --> 00:09:32,266
Helvig, ahoy!

68
00:09:36,239 --> 00:09:37,930
Tommy, drop the ladder.

69
00:09:39,068 --> 00:09:40,472
Ladder down.

70
00:10:00,605 --> 00:10:01,644
Move out of the way for us.

71
00:10:01,764 --> 00:10:03,782
Hello chief. Have a good trip?

72
00:10:06,080 --> 00:10:09,288
Captain Andersen? I've got a telegram
for you from your owners.

73
00:10:10,361 --> 00:10:12,809
I'm Lieutenant-Commander Ellis and
this is Lieutenant-Commander Ashton.

74
00:10:13,947 --> 00:10:15,957
I can't say I'm glad to see you,
gentlemen.

75
00:10:16,167 --> 00:10:17,517
We brought you some English
newspapers Captain.

76
00:10:17,724 --> 00:10:19,733
Thank you. My passengers will
find them interesting.

77
00:10:20,104 --> 00:10:22,042
We shall want to see your
ship's papers, Captain.

78
00:10:23,233 --> 00:10:24,252
Alright.

79
00:10:38,688 --> 00:10:39,988
Hello chief.

80
00:10:40,845 --> 00:10:44,566
You refused to heave-to Captain.
Any particular reason?

81
00:10:45,408 --> 00:10:48,647
For the reason that I didn't want to
lose time with your contraband control.

82
00:10:50,458 --> 00:10:52,833
Radio-log sir, radio-cabin seal, sir.
─ Thank you.

83
00:10:56,891 --> 00:10:58,091
What's your cargo Captain?

84
00:10:58,475 --> 00:11:00,495
Iodine and medical supplies.

85
00:11:00,615 --> 00:11:03,188
Crude medical supplies.
─ Yes, crude medical supplies.

86
00:11:05,036 --> 00:11:07,720
My country has had no shipments
since the war.

87
00:11:09,913 --> 00:11:12,697
I can see your point Captain.
─ I wonder if you can.

88
00:11:13,017 --> 00:11:17,302
You see, the unfortunate thing about war
is that neutrals sometime have to suffer.

89
00:11:17,802 --> 00:11:20,477
They may be carrying goods for our
enemies and we have to see that they don't.

90
00:11:21,097 --> 00:11:25,745
It means inconvenience and delay, but it's
better than putting a torpedo into you.

91
00:11:26,555 --> 00:11:27,692
I appreciate that.

92
00:11:27,956 --> 00:11:29,920
Anyway, those are our orders,
and we had to stop you.

93
00:11:31,261 --> 00:11:33,107
What would you have done
in our place, Captain?

94
00:11:34,281 --> 00:11:35,782
Orders are orders.

95
00:11:36,783 --> 00:11:38,866
What would you have done in my place,
Lieutenant-Commander?

96
00:11:39,403 --> 00:11:40,610
Run away.

97
00:11:44,025 --> 00:11:45,886
Cigar?
─ Do you mind if I stick to my pipe?

98
00:11:46,239 --> 00:11:47,740
Not at all. I'll stick to mine.

99
00:11:50,188 --> 00:11:51,963
Ship's manifest.
─ I'll update that.

100
00:11:52,307 --> 00:11:53,439
Yes, here.

101
00:12:06,616 --> 00:12:09,163
Consigned to the order of
the Danish Government.

102
00:12:10,172 --> 00:12:13,479
???? 525 tons, packed in bales.

103
00:12:13,784 --> 00:12:14,995
Yes.

104
00:12:16,684 --> 00:12:20,741
Crude iodine .. 504 tons.

105
00:12:21,488 --> 00:12:23,944
That's a big shipment Captain.
─ The biggest yet.

106
00:12:24,219 --> 00:12:26,147
Uhuh, and very valuable to my country.

107
00:12:26,511 --> 00:12:28,640
Yes, valuable to any country.

108
00:12:30,436 --> 00:12:33,726
???? in bag, 1610 tons.

109
00:12:36,217 --> 00:12:40,133
???? - 268 tons, 28 tons on deck.

110
00:12:41,403 --> 00:12:42,922
Do you know what your
cargo's worth, Captain?

111
00:12:43,788 --> 00:12:45,398
Certainly. 40 million kroner.

112
00:12:45,662 --> 00:12:47,782
Yes, about 2 million pounds sterling.

113
00:12:51,883 --> 00:12:53,166
[ door knocks ]

114
00:12:53,748 --> 00:12:54,721
Yes?

115
00:12:55,349 --> 00:12:58,382
Your turn next. He was simply charming.
─ Good.

116
00:13:21,641 --> 00:13:23,725
You are English by birth Mrs Sorenson?

117
00:13:24,453 --> 00:13:26,882
Yes, my husband is Danish and we lived
for some time in America.

118
00:13:27,291 --> 00:13:28,729
Is your husband still in America?

119
00:13:29,247 --> 00:13:31,412
No, he lives in Denmark.
I live in America.

120
00:13:31,644 --> 00:13:34,246
You cross the Atlantic very frequently?
─ Yes, I do.

121
00:13:34,655 --> 00:13:36,320
Perhaps you have some business that ..

122
00:13:36,548 --> 00:13:38,267
My husband has the custody of our child.

123
00:13:38,586 --> 00:13:40,396
And I am allowed to visit her at
frequent intervals.

124
00:13:40,969 --> 00:13:42,006
I see.

125
00:13:42,585 --> 00:13:45,741
Thank you Mrs Sorenson. Please ask
Miss Karoly to come in now.

126
00:13:46,052 --> 00:13:46,970
Certainly.

127
00:13:49,403 --> 00:13:51,549
You passed Puerto Blanco on the tenth.

128
00:13:52,622 --> 00:13:55,550
Then ???? the twenty-fourth
and New York the sixth.

129
00:13:55,951 --> 00:13:56,898
A roundabout route, Captain?

130
00:13:57,214 --> 00:13:59,419
Owner's orders. Had to pick up Red-Cross
supplies in New York.

131
00:13:59,775 --> 00:14:02,885
It's marked down Fred. Independent manifest.

132
00:14:03,005 --> 00:14:05,915
32 tons, packed in special cases.
Consigned to Germany.

133
00:14:06,164 --> 00:14:08,447
Under the International Red-Cross agreement.
─ Oh yes, quite.

134
00:14:09,530 --> 00:14:12,682
Engineer's logbook, sir. Lieutenant says,
shall he proceed with the search, sir?

135
00:14:13,070 --> 00:14:14,816
Yes please, Tell him "General Examination".

136
00:14:15,211 --> 00:14:16,066
Oh one moment Church.

137
00:14:16,275 --> 00:14:19,560
Captain, as a formality we shall need some
hatches opened. Will you give the orders?

138
00:14:19,851 --> 00:14:20,906
Uhuh.

139
00:14:27,385 --> 00:14:28,413
He's alright.

140
00:14:29,620 --> 00:14:31,988
Thank you Mrs Abo, that is all.
─ Thank you.

141
00:14:34,117 --> 00:14:35,365
Rather cute.
─ What?

142
00:14:35,610 --> 00:14:36,402
Mrs Abo.

143
00:14:36,639 --> 00:14:39,040
How do you think she came to marry
a professor with a Finnish name?

144
00:14:39,295 --> 00:14:41,784
Oh, I can tell you that sir.
She was his only pupil.

145
00:14:42,079 --> 00:14:42,867
Ha!

146
00:14:43,275 --> 00:14:46,231
There's only one passenger left, sir.
─ Ah, Mr Pidgeon.

147
00:14:54,197 --> 00:14:57,190
Surely, surely your name is English,
Mr Pidgeon?

148
00:14:57,672 --> 00:14:59,055
Correct, I was born in the old country.

149
00:14:59,175 --> 00:15:01,590
And your business takes you abroad?
─ Hmm. On and off.

150
00:15:02,103 --> 00:15:04,168
You are a "talent scout" Mr Pidgeon?

151
00:15:04,770 --> 00:15:05,871
When the mood takes me.

152
00:15:06,399 --> 00:15:08,910
What kind of talent do you
 scout Mr Pidgeon?

153
00:15:09,237 --> 00:15:10,334
Acts ..

154
00:15:12,476 --> 00:15:13,886
Variety acts.

155
00:15:14,626 --> 00:15:18,218
Oh, then have these Hungarian artists
been engaged by you?

156
00:15:19,710 --> 00:15:21,629
I'm only interested in the big time.

157
00:15:22,868 --> 00:15:24,970
You travel a great deal to the United States?

158
00:15:26,371 --> 00:15:28,418
I bring the acts over.

159
00:15:29,328 --> 00:15:30,747
Not so easy these days.

160
00:15:31,529 --> 00:15:32,958
Per Ardua Ad Astra.

161
00:15:34,065 --> 00:15:35,025
Thank you Mr Pidgeon.

162
00:15:35,596 --> 00:15:36,728
Okay.

163
00:15:42,761 --> 00:15:46,611
Mr Skold, inform the passengers that while
in port they must black out all lights.

164
00:15:46,955 --> 00:15:48,312
Yes sir. Allow me sir.

165
00:15:49,387 --> 00:15:51,143
Commander, do you think we should
stay here long?

166
00:15:51,352 --> 00:15:52,162
Can't say.

167
00:15:52,282 --> 00:15:56,019
You see, I have a brother in London,
and I'm his favorite brother.

168
00:15:56,139 --> 00:15:59,197
In that case, perhaps our search party
will be able to find some contraband.

169
00:15:59,424 --> 00:16:00,907
Oh that would be splendid, sir.

170
00:16:10,975 --> 00:16:13,450
Skipper. You're wanted in the saloon sir.

171
00:16:18,920 --> 00:16:20,452
Do sit down Captain.
─ Thank you.

172
00:16:25,808 --> 00:16:29,311
Well Captain, we've examined the ship's
papers, the passengers and your cargo.

173
00:16:30,149 --> 00:16:33,558
The papers are in order and the officers
are satisfied with your passengers.

174
00:16:35,065 --> 00:16:36,863
But the cargo is contraband.

175
00:16:39,512 --> 00:16:44,017
But I have here an Admiralty list of ships
to be passed through quickly on arrival.

176
00:16:44,934 --> 00:16:46,459
Your ship, Captain, is among them.

177
00:16:47,924 --> 00:16:52,492
It only remains that you satisfy us that
your cargo is for your country alone.

178
00:16:52,919 --> 00:16:53,856
How long will that take?

179
00:16:54,152 --> 00:16:56,540
The Ministry Of Economic Warfare
will give that answer tonight.

180
00:16:56,932 --> 00:16:58,615
So, there will be nothing to stop
you sailing in the morning.

181
00:16:58,897 --> 00:17:01,536
That would be splendid .. steward!

182
00:17:02,937 --> 00:17:05,784
My owners asked me to get in touch with
our agent here. Can you help us?

183
00:17:06,228 --> 00:17:07,793
Going to stretch your legs tonight
Captain?

184
00:17:08,147 --> 00:17:08,889
Go ashore?

185
00:17:09,227 --> 00:17:10,429
Yes, I can manage.

186
00:17:10,874 --> 00:17:12,554
How about dinner afterwards?
─ Very good of you.

187
00:17:12,810 --> 00:17:13,715
There's no duty-boat free.

188
00:17:14,020 --> 00:17:15,497
We'll arrange for a local man to take you.

189
00:17:15,948 --> 00:17:17,976
You'll need a couple of Landing Passes.

190
00:17:20,094 --> 00:17:22,416
Gentlemen.
─ Oh very good, very nice.

191
00:17:27,831 --> 00:17:30,818
You understand Captain Andersen, until you
get your clearance papers in the morning ..

192
00:17:31,236 --> 00:17:33,919
We shall hold you responsible for
the ship and everyone in her.

193
00:17:34,181 --> 00:17:36,820
Perfectly. When will the boat be here?
─ About six.

194
00:17:37,216 --> 00:17:38,636
Four bells.

195
00:18:06,595 --> 00:18:08,377
[ door knocks ]

196
00:18:09,024 --> 00:18:10,169
Come in.

197
00:18:11,568 --> 00:18:12,420
Ready skipper?

198
00:18:12,777 --> 00:18:14,867
Is the motor boat here?
─ Sure, it came half an hour ago.

199
00:18:15,183 --> 00:18:17,616
Then let's go.
─ Oh don't forget the landing-passes.

200
00:18:18,365 --> 00:18:21,073
I thought you had taken them.
─ Me? No ..

201
00:18:21,403 --> 00:18:22,970
They were lying on the desk.

202
00:18:23,740 --> 00:18:26,366
You sure you didn't put them in a drawer?
─ Of course I'm sure.

203
00:18:33,833 --> 00:18:34,832
They can't have flown away.

204
00:18:35,078 --> 00:18:36,772
I saw them lying there, but
I didn't touch them.

205
00:18:37,643 --> 00:18:40,581
You didn't .. but somebody else did.

206
00:18:41,928 --> 00:18:43,155
Anyway, how could we get ashore?

207
00:18:43,415 --> 00:18:46,266
My goodness. I had a boat along
to do a paint-job.

208
00:18:51,448 --> 00:18:54,122
Never mind the ship's boat. Go and see if
the motor-boat is still there.

209
00:18:54,442 --> 00:18:57,248
The motor-boat? My goodness.

210
00:19:11,690 --> 00:19:12,464
Gone!

211
00:19:13,097 --> 00:19:16,907
I though so .. we'll start with
the passengers.

212
00:19:18,552 --> 00:19:20,504
You take the port cabins,
I'll take the starboard.

213
00:19:20,750 --> 00:19:21,823
Yes sir.

214
00:19:26,327 --> 00:19:27,681
Come in.

215
00:19:28,869 --> 00:19:30,497
Hello Captain.
─ I beg your pardon.

216
00:19:37,569 --> 00:19:39,050
Mrs Sorenson?

217
00:20:29,769 --> 00:20:31,749
Mr Pidgeon has flown.

218
00:20:32,215 --> 00:20:33,526
Nowhere on the ship?
─ Nope.

219
00:20:33,825 --> 00:20:35,242
Sure?
─ Yes.

220
00:20:36,001 --> 00:20:37,963
Did you see Mrs Sorenson anywhere?

221
00:20:38,825 --> 00:20:39,634
No.

222
00:20:40,417 --> 00:20:42,247
Mrs Sorenson, and Mr Pidgeon.

223
00:20:43,470 --> 00:20:44,746
Does it make sense to you?

224
00:20:45,636 --> 00:20:47,959
No, during the whole voyage they
never once spoke to each other.

225
00:20:48,927 --> 00:20:51,795
I wonder what she tore out of here?
It's the local paper.

226
00:20:52,595 --> 00:20:53,862
If we had another copy we could tell.

227
00:20:57,706 --> 00:20:59,140
Just a minute.

228
00:21:01,428 --> 00:21:02,290
Enter.

229
00:21:02,774 --> 00:21:03,737
May I borrow your newspaper?

230
00:21:03,896 --> 00:21:06,196
Certainly Captain, but you can
read it here Captain.

231
00:21:08,624 --> 00:21:09,382
Silly!

232
00:21:09,786 --> 00:21:12,681
Now we shall see.
─ Page twelve.

233
00:21:19,356 --> 00:21:20,112
I've got it.

234
00:21:20,232 --> 00:21:21,912
"If you suffer from indigestion,
take Tono's Tonic Powder."

235
00:21:22,207 --> 00:21:24,698
"By Mrs J Wright. I was worn out.
My husband gave me up, my doctor .."

236
00:21:25,232 --> 00:21:27,273
What have you got there?
─ I don't know.

237
00:21:30,343 --> 00:21:31,126
What is it, sir?

238
00:21:31,574 --> 00:21:34,117
Revised timetable of trains to London.

239
00:21:34,451 --> 00:21:38,682
London. I can see the departure for 7:15.

240
00:21:39,162 --> 00:21:41,861
Arrives London Victoria 9:15.

241
00:21:42,835 --> 00:21:44,233
7:15.

242
00:21:45,197 --> 00:21:48,496
I'll stop them catching that train if
I have to swim ashore.

243
00:22:03,501 --> 00:22:08,797
Mrs Sorenson .. and Mr Pidgeon.

244
00:22:15,043 --> 00:22:17,496
Guard ship.

245
00:22:53,310 --> 00:22:55,357
What will happen when we don't
turn up to dinner?

246
00:22:55,672 --> 00:22:58,104
You will turn up, I'm going to
the railway station.

247
00:22:58,724 --> 00:23:00,220
What shall I tell of our action
to the Commander?

248
00:23:00,437 --> 00:23:02,091
Tell him whatever you like.

249
00:23:04,204 --> 00:23:08,216
Mrs Sorenson .. and Mr Pidgeon.

250
00:23:15,622 --> 00:23:18,034
Come on, Mata Hari, we've got exactly
a minute to catch that train.

251
00:23:18,250 --> 00:23:20,100
I know but .. hello?

252
00:23:22,744 --> 00:23:25,568
Hello. Can I speak to Mrs Clayton please?

253
00:23:25,867 --> 00:23:27,231
This is the secretary speaking.

254
00:23:27,952 --> 00:23:29,725
No, Mrs Clayton is not home at the moment.

255
00:23:30,455 --> 00:23:33,358
She's in town, but she's out giving
a first-aid lecture. Who is that, please?

256
00:23:33,719 --> 00:23:35,188
This is her niece Miss Clayton.

257
00:23:36,832 --> 00:23:38,011
When will Mrs Clayton be back?

258
00:23:38,513 --> 00:23:40,140
I think about half past ten Miss Clayton.

259
00:23:40,299 --> 00:23:42,938
Will you tell her I will be in London at
that time. I will have a friend with me.

260
00:23:43,343 --> 00:23:44,170
Very good.

261
00:23:44,750 --> 00:23:45,423
I don't know you, do I?

262
00:23:45,954 --> 00:23:48,415
No. I've only been with Mrs Clayton for
a month.

263
00:23:49,459 --> 00:23:50,473
My name is Lang.

264
00:23:50,799 --> 00:23:52,849
Come on. Yap, yap, yap.

265
00:23:53,341 --> 00:23:54,159
Goodbye.

266
00:24:01,811 --> 00:24:03,571
No. Stay there.

267
00:25:06,899 --> 00:25:09,380
Would you mind shutting that door, sir.
There's a draught.

268
00:25:24,404 --> 00:25:25,829
What's the next stop?
─ London, sir.

269
00:25:38,883 --> 00:25:39,983
Hello Rickman. Back?

270
00:25:40,247 --> 00:25:42,279
No, I'm paddling a canoe up Niagara Falls.

271
00:25:42,420 --> 00:25:44,303
Funny, aren't you. How many ships
in the anchorage?

272
00:25:44,511 --> 00:25:45,487
None. All boarders.

273
00:25:45,783 --> 00:25:47,791
Do you want the Ocean Breeze or
Silver Fox for tomorrow morning?

274
00:25:48,083 --> 00:25:50,784
What, those old tubs? No I want
Saucy Sally at six-thirty sharp.

275
00:25:51,004 --> 00:25:53,155
Broken crankshaft.
─ Hell, that's the third time.

276
00:25:53,406 --> 00:25:55,367
I can do My Girl for the six-thirty.

277
00:25:55,541 --> 00:25:57,536
Well, you have got a bunch
of old crocks, haven't you.

278
00:25:58,083 --> 00:26:00,145
Any more letters or telegrams?
─ Yes, but wait until I've finished.

279
00:26:00,391 --> 00:26:01,734
Oh, it's seven o'clock now.

280
00:26:01,866 --> 00:26:03,761
Why did Horace ever sell his farm
and go to sea?

281
00:26:04,046 --> 00:26:05,749
Never mind, you'll be home by nine,
my good man.

282
00:26:08,072 --> 00:26:09,520
You finished the boarding report
on the Zandam?

283
00:26:09,640 --> 00:26:10,760
Two minutes.

284
00:26:11,124 --> 00:26:11,880
How'd you expect me to read this?

285
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:14,135
How do you expect me to do
copper-plate with chilblains?

286
00:26:16,564 --> 00:26:17,497
Lieutenant-Commander Ellis?

287
00:26:17,699 --> 00:26:20,356
Straight along the passage, through
the swing-doors, turn right.

288
00:26:27,967 --> 00:26:29,304
Well, find anything?
─ Yes, sir.

289
00:26:29,717 --> 00:26:30,888
A lot of stuff that wasn't manifested.

290
00:26:31,169 --> 00:26:31,934
Cases of machinery?

291
00:26:32,093 --> 00:26:34,961
Yes, sir. Looks like parts of an aeroplane.
─ I thought so.

292
00:26:36,393 --> 00:26:38,223
Ge me M.E.W. on the direct line.

293
00:26:49,260 --> 00:26:51,231
Lieutenant-Commander Ellis, sir.

294
00:27:11,940 --> 00:27:14,155
Hello Mr Skold.
─ May I present our agent.

295
00:27:14,361 --> 00:27:16,362
Oh, we know about him.
─ Hello sonny-boy.

296
00:27:16,617 --> 00:27:17,435
Where's the skipper?

297
00:27:17,593 --> 00:27:19,107
He's staying on board, sir.
He's not doing very well.

298
00:27:19,238 --> 00:27:20,567
Why, what's wrong with him?
He looked alright.

299
00:27:20,708 --> 00:27:23,725
He's awfully ill now. He keeps on
having attacks. It's stomach ache.

300
00:27:24,309 --> 00:27:26,166
And when he gets stomach aches,
he's no good for anything.

301
00:27:26,465 --> 00:27:28,644
He should drink gin.
Waiter, four pink gins.

302
00:27:28,911 --> 00:27:31,084
Can we send out a doctor?
─ No. He hates doctors.

303
00:27:31,334 --> 00:27:35,020
So do I. Only two things worth a
twopenny-damn. Gin, and a good circulation.

304
00:27:46,087 --> 00:27:47,978
Which side do we get out, mummy?
─ I don't know dear.

305
00:27:50,166 --> 00:27:51,265
It's this side mummy.

306
00:27:53,721 --> 00:27:55,345
Victoria. Victoria.

307
00:27:56,940 --> 00:27:59,194
Alright governor.
─ Sorry.

308
00:28:12,702 --> 00:28:14,149
The lady has the tickets.

309
00:28:23,761 --> 00:28:26,227
How dare you go ashore! How dare
you steal the two landing passes!

310
00:28:26,594 --> 00:28:28,078
How dare you go ashore without
landing passes!

311
00:28:28,198 --> 00:28:29,501
Do you know what I could do to you?

312
00:28:29,621 --> 00:28:30,237
For what?

313
00:28:30,852 --> 00:28:31,961
You don't want to be mixed up with
the police do you?

314
00:28:32,102 --> 00:28:33,510
No, do you?
─ No, I don't.

315
00:28:33,712 --> 00:28:35,872
Where's Mr Pidgeon?
─ Mr Pidgeon?

316
00:28:36,312 --> 00:28:37,288


317
00:28:36,312 --> 00:28:37,323
I don't know anything about Mr Pidgeon.

318
00:28:37,517 --> 00:28:39,329
I suppose he came to London to
engage Variety acts?

319
00:28:39,488 --> 00:28:40,076
That's his business.

320
00:28:40,352 --> 00:28:44,330
What a coincidence that you two stole
the same landing passes at the same time.

321
00:28:44,515 --> 00:28:46,873
To use the same motorboat,
to travel on the same train.

322
00:28:47,110 --> 00:28:47,841
You don't have to believe it.

323
00:28:48,122 --> 00:28:50,673
I believe that if I stick with you,
we shall meet Mr Pidgeon again.

324
00:28:50,974 --> 00:28:52,309
Do you?
─ Yes, I do.

325
00:28:52,742 --> 00:28:55,505
Look. I promise I'll be back on the
ship before morning. My word of honor.

326
00:28:55,743 --> 00:28:57,168
To play cards?

327
00:29:03,325 --> 00:29:06,209
10:10. .. 12:05 .. 03:30

328
00:29:06,795 --> 00:29:08,758
So we leave at ten past ten.
─ Or five past twelve.

329
00:29:09,064 --> 00:29:11,440
And if we don't find Mr Pidgeon
by 3:30 we all go to jail.

330
00:29:11,652 --> 00:29:14,643
And no doubt, we shall find him there.
Meanwhile, where you go, I go.

331
00:29:36,683 --> 00:29:38,680
Well, it was worth trying.

332
00:29:39,005 --> 00:29:42,357
Gas-mask cases! Torches! Gas-mask cases!
Don't forget the torches.

333
00:29:42,995 --> 00:29:45,584
Don't forget your torches.
Don't forget your gas-mask cases.

334
00:29:45,951 --> 00:29:48,803
Torches! Gas-mask cases. Here,
a nice torch for the blackout.

335
00:29:49,110 --> 00:29:51,442
A ever-lasting battery and a beam
as strong as a searchlight.

336
00:29:51,658 --> 00:29:52,967
If you buy one of these, you will
never lose your way.

337
00:29:53,341 --> 00:29:55,103
I don't want a torch!
─ But it will guide your way home, sir.

338
00:29:55,348 --> 00:29:56,636
It will guide the young lady
home as well, sir.

339
00:29:56,696 --> 00:29:57,974
Only half-a-dollar, sir.
─ I'll buy a torch.

340
00:29:58,143 --> 00:29:59,787
Thank you lady .. see that beam!

341
00:30:01,149 --> 00:30:02,721
Thank you.
─ Thank you, lady.

342
00:30:04,201 --> 00:30:05,688
What about a nice-looking gas-mask
case Miss?

343
00:30:05,926 --> 00:30:06,752
Handy for putting sandwiches in.

344
00:30:06,925 --> 00:30:09,508
I need another torch, for the gentleman.
─ I don't need a torch.

345
00:30:09,628 --> 00:30:11,775
Everybody needs a torch in the blackout.
Thank you.

346
00:30:12,465 --> 00:30:13,822
Thank you lady.

347
00:30:15,168 --> 00:30:15,815
Shine your torch!

348
00:30:16,066 --> 00:30:20,501
Oh, many times I've stood on my bridge
in the Atlantic on a night like this.

349
00:30:20,830 --> 00:30:23,218
Oh, I beg your pardon!
─ Hey, look where you're going!

350
00:30:23,694 --> 00:30:26,910
Obviously you're better in the middle of
the Atlantic. Now will you shine your torch?

351
00:30:28,890 --> 00:30:31,688
This is Buckingham Palace Road.
─ You really know where we are?

352
00:30:32,052 --> 00:30:33,552
Of course.
─ Amazing.

353
00:30:33,780 --> 00:30:36,173
But I wouldn't be much use in the
middle of the Atlantic.

354
00:30:38,993 --> 00:30:41,474
"Will that gentleman shine his
torch down please."

355
00:30:42,675 --> 00:30:44,156
A police car.
─ Oh.

356
00:30:48,921 --> 00:30:50,529
Coming?

357
00:31:07,264 --> 00:31:08,655
Where are we going?
─ To the bus-stop.

358
00:31:08,861 --> 00:31:11,767
Wait a minute. Are we going by bus?
─ I'm going by bus.

359
00:31:19,918 --> 00:31:23,009
Hyde Park Corner, Ritz Hotel, Bond Street
and Oxford Circus.

360
00:31:25,293 --> 00:31:26,515
Hold tight!

361
00:31:35,144 --> 00:31:36,737
I beg your pardon.

362
00:31:37,042 --> 00:31:39,966
Fares please .. fares please.

363
00:31:44,534 --> 00:31:47,743
Any more fares please .. fares please.

364
00:31:49,033 --> 00:31:50,303
Fare please!

365
00:31:51,779 --> 00:31:54,004
A threepenny and a a penny one please.

366
00:31:59,962 --> 00:32:01,763
Thank you. Any more fares please?

367
00:32:03,014 --> 00:32:04,274
The penny one is for you.

368
00:32:06,457 --> 00:32:08,505
You think you're very clever don't you.

369
00:32:09,450 --> 00:32:11,940
How do expect to get about London
in the blackout without any money?

370
00:32:12,462 --> 00:32:14,382
I can get all the money I need.

371
00:32:15,076 --> 00:32:17,901
And I'll buy you such a dinner as you've
never had in your life.

372
00:32:18,394 --> 00:32:20,559
Big words.
─ Big dinner.

373
00:32:21,632 --> 00:32:22,883
Are you hungry?

374
00:32:24,064 --> 00:32:25,905
As a matter of fact, I'm starving.

375
00:32:26,279 --> 00:32:27,706
Well, let's take a taxi.

376
00:32:29,302 --> 00:32:31,488
Alright. But I'm not paying for it.

377
00:32:31,811 --> 00:32:33,179
Hyde Park Corner ..

378
00:32:38,791 --> 00:32:40,886
Taxi .. yes .. taxi.

379
00:32:41,653 --> 00:32:42,825
Stick to it.

380
00:32:44,500 --> 00:32:45,377
Taxi!

381
00:32:46,056 --> 00:32:47,074
Here's one .. taxi.

382
00:32:47,311 --> 00:32:48,787
Go home crackers.

383
00:32:49,319 --> 00:32:50,512
Taxi!

384
00:32:55,280 --> 00:32:56,432
Here's one .. you see?

385
00:32:56,737 --> 00:32:58,837
Can we give you a lift .. or something?
─ No!

386
00:32:59,759 --> 00:33:01,275
You'd better take a taxi.

387
00:33:03,775 --> 00:33:05,508
Taxi!

388
00:33:05,934 --> 00:33:07,233
Cab! Cab!

389
00:33:07,689 --> 00:33:09,576
It's a Hansome. Cabby ..

390
00:33:20,514 --> 00:33:21,996
Where to?
─ The Three Kings.

391
00:33:22,262 --> 00:33:23,664
The three what?
─ Three Kings.

392
00:33:24,009 --> 00:33:24,826
The Three Vikings.

393
00:33:25,112 --> 00:33:26,913
Oh, the Danish place? Albany Street?

394
00:33:27,201 --> 00:33:28,766
Okay, come on me old boy.

395
00:33:33,640 --> 00:33:35,194
Three Vikings ..

396
00:33:58,140 --> 00:34:00,335
Good evening.
─ Good evening.

397
00:34:01,890 --> 00:34:03,465
No gas-masks?
─ We have no gas-masks.

398
00:34:03,767 --> 00:34:05,111
Two sir?
─ Yes, two.

399
00:34:09,998 --> 00:34:13,414
Haven't you got a table by the wall?
─ I'm so sorry sir. They are all taken.

400
00:34:21,655 --> 00:34:23,782
We should like to talk to the proprietor.
─ Yes, sir.

401
00:34:25,199 --> 00:34:28,438
He's bound to know what is good in
his own restaurant. Isn't he?

402
00:34:41,394 --> 00:34:44,139
Order! Order! I must have order in
my kitchen!

403
00:34:44,395 --> 00:34:46,159
Mr Skold, f you please.
─ What is it?

404
00:34:46,375 --> 00:34:48,320
A customer wishes to speak
to you Mr Skold.

405
00:34:48,440 --> 00:34:50,457
OH what is wrong again?
What is wrong again?

406
00:34:50,577 --> 00:34:53,597
Don't you know by now that I hate
to be disturbed. Tell him to go to hell.

407
00:34:54,061 --> 00:34:55,667
But be polite. Polite!

408
00:35:00,503 --> 00:35:02,659
Stir for two minutes, add cream,
don't stir, serve.

409
00:35:02,887 --> 00:35:04,864
Uncle Erik, you're wanted on
the telephone. It's urgent.

410
00:35:05,142 --> 00:35:07,880
Oh, are you also an idiot? I thought at
least my kitchen was clean of idiots.

411
00:35:08,108 --> 00:35:09,510
Don't you see I have no time.

412
00:35:09,630 --> 00:35:14,225
I must not be disturbed in my kitchen,
and now I am disturbed. Once is enough.

413
00:35:14,523 --> 00:35:18,538
Tell the silly fool to ring tonight after
midnight. But be polite. Very polite.

414
00:35:18,741 --> 00:35:20,206
But it is urgent Uncle Erik.

415
00:35:20,521 --> 00:35:21,561
Oh ..

416
00:35:36,436 --> 00:35:38,375
Uncle Erik .. please!

417
00:35:43,179 --> 00:35:44,862
Good evening.
─ Good evening Mr Skold.

418
00:35:45,118 --> 00:35:47,274
This is Mr Skold, proprietor of
the Three Vikings.

419
00:35:47,520 --> 00:35:50,089
I am Captain Andersen of the Helvig.
This is Mrs Sorenson.

420
00:35:50,306 --> 00:35:51,615
Mrs Sorenson is a passenger on my ship.

421
00:35:51,822 --> 00:35:53,091
Good evening.
─ Good evening.

422
00:35:53,314 --> 00:35:56,464
What a surprise Captain, and what
a pleasure, a very great pleasure.

423
00:35:56,721 --> 00:35:58,109
I hope nothing has happened to the Helvig.

424
00:35:58,326 --> 00:36:00,579
Oh no .. and your brother sends
you his love.

425
00:36:01,260 --> 00:36:04,508
My brother? Now you must tell me
everything please.

426
00:36:04,773 --> 00:36:08,838
What is it? Why don't you take the order?
You must have a drink with me.

427
00:36:09,203 --> 00:36:10,834
Oh, would you like to come and
see my cold tables?

428
00:36:10,954 --> 00:36:12,370
Certainly!
─ Come.

429
00:36:13,528 --> 00:36:17,390
Now you must have some of this,
and some of that. That is wonderful.

430
00:36:18,627 --> 00:36:21,987
By the way, Mr Skold, I came ashore in
such a hurry I have no money.

431
00:36:24,660 --> 00:36:26,235
No money?

432
00:36:34,678 --> 00:36:38,626
So .. you are Captain Andersen in the
ship where my brother is a cook?

433
00:36:39,193 --> 00:36:41,103
Cook?
─ Or is he something else?

434
00:36:41,430 --> 00:36:43,163
Of course he's something else.
─ Ah, but what?

435
00:36:43,463 --> 00:36:45,668
Why, First Officer.
─ Ah, please, excuse.

436
00:36:46,012 --> 00:36:48,437
But the Helvig must be since eight
days in Copenhagen?

437
00:36:48,653 --> 00:36:51,173
But she's not.
─ Where is she, if she's not?

438
00:36:51,380 --> 00:36:54,560
That's a secret, and it's also a secret
that I'm here in London.

439
00:36:54,995 --> 00:36:57,660
Ah, so. It is a secret. Of course,
I don't mention it.

440
00:36:58,086 --> 00:37:01,929
Is it also a secret why my brother did
not come to see me? My favorite brother?

441
00:37:02,289 --> 00:37:04,735
Is it also a secret why he did not wire,
why he did not write?

442
00:37:05,010 --> 00:37:07,639
How could he write, if we only
arrived this afternoon ..

443
00:37:08,227 --> 00:37:09,404
No trouble.
─ Uncle Erik.

444
00:37:09,630 --> 00:37:11,215
Go away! What are you doing in
the restaurant?

445
00:37:11,520 --> 00:37:14,173
So, he could not wire, he could not write
and he could not come.

446
00:37:14,293 --> 00:37:16,366
Why could he not come when a
passenger could come?

447
00:37:16,718 --> 00:37:19,237
Because I am the Captain and I have
forbidden him to come.

448
00:37:19,451 --> 00:37:22,693
And you expect favors of me when you
forbid my brother to come and see me?

449
00:37:23,023 --> 00:37:24,874
Excuse me Mr Skold, I couldn't
help hearing.

450
00:37:24,994 --> 00:37:27,040
I paid the gent's cab fare.
Three bob and a tanner.

451
00:37:27,322 --> 00:37:30,773
Damn your bobs and tanners! There is more
important business here to be discussed.

452
00:37:30,975 --> 00:37:32,125
Well, I couldn't help hearing.

453
00:37:32,367 --> 00:37:33,745
Please Uncle Erik.

454
00:37:34,204 --> 00:37:36,931
Now look here Mr Skold.
You seem to doubt my word.

455
00:37:37,158 --> 00:37:39,983
I do now seem, and I do doubt!
And why should I believe you?

456
00:37:40,270 --> 00:37:43,205
Mr Skold, the gentleman on the
telephone is a tall call.

457
00:37:43,325 --> 00:37:45,196
If he speaks from America, let him.
I should care?

458
00:37:45,501 --> 00:37:47,145
But it is your brother Mr Skold!

459
00:37:47,396 --> 00:37:49,431
Your brother Axel, Mr Skold.

460
00:37:49,551 --> 00:37:50,447
Axel? Why the?

461
00:37:50,567 --> 00:37:52,342
I told you it was urgent Mr Skold.

462
00:37:52,462 --> 00:37:53,435
Where is the phone?

463
00:37:56,459 --> 00:38:00,731
Hello? Hello? Hello Axel?
It's me, Andersen.

464
00:38:01,292 --> 00:38:04,816
Here in London. Yes, he's here.
Oh yes, I like it very much.

465
00:38:05,348 --> 00:38:07,740
Listen, Axel, did you leave
the boat tied up?

466
00:38:08,414 --> 00:38:10,984
Good .. yes I had to follow them.

467
00:38:11,407 --> 00:38:15,177
No, Pidgeon is missing, but I've got her.
She's sitting in the restaurant and she ..

468
00:38:16,463 --> 00:38:19,141
Speak to your brother.
─ Erik, Erik, Erik!

469
00:38:19,466 --> 00:38:22,688
Oh Axel, I am so glad to hear
your voice my boy.

470
00:38:23,044 --> 00:38:27,080
Your Captain? Yes, he is a beautiful man.
From the first moment, I liked him.

471
00:38:30,951 --> 00:38:32,355
The lady asked if the gentleman is going.

472
00:38:32,611 --> 00:38:34,186
What lady?
─ Please.

473
00:38:40,373 --> 00:38:41,584
Thank you.

474
00:38:51,723 --> 00:38:52,432
Bon!

475
00:38:52,849 --> 00:38:55,231
Now. What will you have to follow?
─ We haven't ordered yet.

476
00:38:55,448 --> 00:38:56,974
Not ordered. Not ordered?

477
00:39:01,759 --> 00:39:03,728
???? and tomato sauce.

478
00:39:06,906 --> 00:39:07,689
Which do you suggest?

479
00:39:07,809 --> 00:39:11,892
This,and this and that, are all ready,
but that, that is wonderful.

480
00:39:12,184 --> 00:39:15,249
But then I usually prepare that myself
and I would have to leave you.

481
00:39:15,470 --> 00:39:17,378
Oh pity.
─ We should love to taste it.

482
00:39:18,058 --> 00:39:20,883
Well don't worry, don't worry.
You shall see, in fifteen minutes.

483
00:39:21,314 --> 00:39:23,885
???? ???? ?????

484
00:39:24,328 --> 00:39:25,519
Follow me.

485
00:39:28,707 --> 00:39:29,898
How is Axel the Mate?

486
00:39:30,321 --> 00:39:33,439
He seemed to have dined well.
─ Not so well as us.

487
00:39:34,620 --> 00:39:36,825
He has a clear conscience.
─ No he hasn't.

488
00:39:37,099 --> 00:39:38,408
Why?

489
00:39:38,812 --> 00:39:41,420
He has to cover my absence.
─ I've put you both on the spot.

490
00:39:41,775 --> 00:39:44,236
I like being on the spot. Skol!
─ Skol!

491
00:39:48,760 --> 00:39:50,610
What else do you like?
─ A small ship.

492
00:39:51,576 --> 00:39:52,924
I suppose you've never tried a big ship?

493
00:39:53,406 --> 00:39:55,424
The bigger the ship, the smaller
the adventure.

494
00:39:55,737 --> 00:39:58,513
The smaller the ship, the bigger the
adventure, but you wouldn't understand.

495
00:39:59,311 --> 00:40:01,073
Because you have childish ideas about life.

496
00:40:01,193 --> 00:40:04,485
Because like so many women you live
only for little excitements, like uh ..

497
00:40:04,786 --> 00:40:05,436
Like what?

498
00:40:05,800 --> 00:40:09,856
Well, like going out every night,
somewhere new, somebody new. Right?

499
00:40:11,234 --> 00:40:13,981
You didn't answer my question.
Did you ever try a big ship?

500
00:40:14,551 --> 00:40:15,397
Of course I did.

501
00:40:15,683 --> 00:40:17,228
And did you ever try being married?

502
00:40:17,977 --> 00:40:21,984
That can be quite a big adventure.
─ Ah, why do women always say that?

503
00:40:22,561 --> 00:40:24,067
Marriage ends adventure.

504
00:40:24,747 --> 00:40:26,479
Why do men always say that?

505
00:40:26,996 --> 00:40:28,679
Hmm! .. Skol!

506
00:40:29,181 --> 00:40:30,264
Skol!

507
00:40:36,479 --> 00:40:38,465
Well, in five minutes our first
train is leaving.

508
00:40:39,763 --> 00:40:40,748
Show me.

509
00:40:44,770 --> 00:40:46,867
Commandante Andersen.
─ Yes.

510
00:40:47,103 --> 00:40:49,623
In the Danish Navy.
─ Uhuh. In the Danish Navy.

511
00:40:49,972 --> 00:40:51,189
But you left it. Why?

512
00:40:51,309 --> 00:40:54,290
The Danish Navy sails around the coast
of Denmark and then back again.

513
00:40:55,501 --> 00:40:57,637
I wanted to sail everywhere
a ship can sail.

514
00:40:58,802 --> 00:41:00,062
But you wouldn't understand that.

515
00:41:01,534 --> 00:41:03,749
The "Bjorn Helm" was a big ship?
─ Hmm.

516
00:41:04,566 --> 00:41:06,180
Six times as big as the Helvig.

517
00:41:08,579 --> 00:41:09,917
That's the winder.

518
00:41:12,399 --> 00:41:13,807
Press it again.

519
00:41:14,616 --> 00:41:18,661
[ musical chimes ]

520
00:41:19,181 --> 00:41:20,236
It's fascinating.

521
00:41:20,660 --> 00:41:23,485
That's the song we officers used
to sing when we went ashore.

522
00:41:23,731 --> 00:41:25,365
The last part especially.

523
00:41:26,507 --> 00:41:28,328
Twice?
─ Twice.

524
00:41:29,229 --> 00:41:33,097
????? ???? ?????

525
00:41:33,461 --> 00:41:36,631
Hoorah, hoorah, hoorah.

526
00:41:36,848 --> 00:41:38,108
Let me try.

527
00:41:41,976 --> 00:41:45,333
????? ???? ?????

528
00:41:45,609 --> 00:41:48,495
Hoorah, hoorah, hoorah.

529
00:41:48,947 --> 00:41:50,203
Now I've got it.

530
00:41:52,310 --> 00:41:56,129
????? ???? ?????

531
00:41:56,579 --> 00:42:00,399
Hoorah, hoorah, hoorah. Skol!

532
00:42:01,442 --> 00:42:02,387
Skol!

533
00:42:03,640 --> 00:42:10,511
[ train whistle ]

534
00:42:13,654 --> 00:42:15,751
Close your eyes when you get outside
and count to ten.

535
00:42:15,958 --> 00:42:17,562
The you will be able to see better
in the blackout.

536
00:42:17,682 --> 00:42:18,970
Thank you Mr Skold, you think
of everything.

537
00:42:19,216 --> 00:42:23,038
Oh it is nothing, nothing at all. And
whenever you come the restaurant is yours.

538
00:42:23,475 --> 00:42:25,237
Goodbye.
─ Goodbye.

539
00:42:29,283 --> 00:42:32,177
Hoorah, hoorah, hoorah.

540
00:42:34,159 --> 00:42:35,931
8 .. 9 .. 10.

541
00:42:37,600 --> 00:42:39,648
Can you see any better?
─ Just as black as it was.

542
00:42:40,170 --> 00:42:40,829
Blacker.

543
00:42:40,949 --> 00:42:42,651
What are you going to do
until five past twelve?

544
00:42:43,261 --> 00:42:45,555
I've got a lot to do.
─ We've have a lot to do.

545
00:42:45,836 --> 00:42:48,101
We have lot to do.
─ What do we do first?

546
00:42:48,672 --> 00:42:50,001
Have a drink?
─ Good.

547
00:42:50,266 --> 00:42:51,881
And the drinks are on me.
─ Good.

548
00:42:52,137 --> 00:42:53,091
Here's your taxi, sir.

549
00:42:53,376 --> 00:42:54,754
And I'll pay for the taxi.

550
00:43:07,690 --> 00:43:09,344
Where are we now?
─ Chester Square

551
00:43:09,595 --> 00:43:11,239
Is it?
─ Look up.

552
00:43:11,757 --> 00:43:15,055


553
00:43:11,761 --> 00:43:14,940
I've never seen the stars so clear
in a big city.

554
00:43:15,193 --> 00:43:17,743
Don't look so high. See that window?

555
00:43:18,235 --> 00:43:20,243
I spent eight years of my life there.

556
00:43:27,527 --> 00:43:30,225
Is anyone at home? Aunt Kate?

557
00:43:31,229 --> 00:43:32,873
This is my aunt's house.
I think you'll like her.

558
00:43:35,192 --> 00:43:36,286
Aunt Kate!

559
00:43:36,778 --> 00:43:39,840
[ do barking ]

560
00:43:40,238 --> 00:43:42,050
It's the boys. They must be in the kitchen.

561
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:50,579
Come on boy .. come on.

562
00:43:51,684 --> 00:43:55,395
Come to me, then. It doesn't look as
if your aunt is at home.

563
00:43:55,647 --> 00:43:58,610
She must be upstairs. Aunt Kate!

564
00:44:00,491 --> 00:44:01,859
Aunt Kate!

565
00:44:04,061 --> 00:44:05,866
At least the secretary ought to be here.

566
00:44:08,235 --> 00:44:09,524
Aunt Kate.

567
00:44:11,178 --> 00:44:12,556
Aunt Kate!

568
00:44:16,170 --> 00:44:17,440
Aunt Kate.

569
00:44:26,165 --> 00:44:28,508
Are you sure you have an aunt,
and not an uncle?

570
00:44:40,742 --> 00:44:42,179
Good evening.

571
00:44:51,134 --> 00:44:53,467
Good evening Mrs Sorenson.
─ I'm Miss Clayton.

572
00:44:53,684 --> 00:44:56,106
You've never heard the name Sorenson?
─ Never in my life.

573
00:44:57,047 --> 00:44:59,695
This is my aunt's house. Who are you?
─ My name is Lang.

574
00:45:00,010 --> 00:45:02,304
You're the secretary. Where is Mrs Clayton?

575
00:45:02,606 --> 00:45:05,024
Sergeant Clayton. Somewhere in
England I believe.

576
00:45:05,228 --> 00:45:08,784
Don't let us waste time Mrs Sorenson.
─ I tell you I am not Mrs Sorenson.

577
00:45:10,247 --> 00:45:12,068
And you, I suppose, are not Mr Pidgeon?

578
00:45:12,915 --> 00:45:14,529
Uh, I'm not Mr Pidgeon.

579
00:45:25,580 --> 00:45:28,336
Sloan 2-7-4-1.
─ I want to speak to Mrs Sorenson.

580
00:45:29,160 --> 00:45:31,897
What name please?
─ Tell her it's Mr Pidgeon. It's urgent.

581
00:45:32,635 --> 00:45:34,417
She's in the bathroom sir.
Can she ring you back?

582
00:45:34,968 --> 00:45:37,703
Ring me back? What the devil for?
She was supposed to be here long ago.

583
00:45:38,008 --> 00:45:38,736
Tell her to hurry.

584
00:45:38,856 --> 00:45:41,040
Where should she ring you sir if she asks?
─ She knows.

585
00:45:41,266 --> 00:45:43,255
Where should she meet you, sir?
─ She knows.

586
00:45:45,821 --> 00:45:47,957
Hello? Hello, hello.

587
00:45:49,758 --> 00:45:51,639
Have you finished?
─ Who is that?

588
00:45:52,062 --> 00:45:53,569
This is the Army And Navy Club, madam.

589
00:45:54,981 --> 00:45:56,979
So Mr Pidgeon is at the
Army And Navy Club.

590
00:45:57,255 --> 00:45:58,564
The Army And Navy Club?

591
00:45:58,899 --> 00:45:59,982
Then who are you?

592
00:46:00,632 --> 00:46:02,167
My name is Andersen.

593
00:46:02,837 --> 00:46:03,673
Hans Andersen.

594
00:46:03,965 --> 00:46:06,151
And we are the Brothers Grimm.

595
00:46:19,807 --> 00:46:22,118
Are they Police?
─ I wish they were.

596
00:46:22,403 --> 00:46:23,702
No talking!

597
00:46:46,032 --> 00:46:49,005
What are you looking at?
─ The stars.

598
00:47:04,826 --> 00:47:05,701
Get out.

599
00:47:08,920 --> 00:47:10,452
Suppose we don't get out?

600
00:47:11,267 --> 00:47:15,037
Yes. As a matter of fact, we feel quite
comfortable where we are.

601
00:47:16,076 --> 00:47:18,665
Yes! We are just beginning to
like it very much.

602
00:47:18,872 --> 00:47:21,825
Get out and stop talking.
─ Who is going to stop me talking?

603
00:47:22,219 --> 00:47:25,615
We are in a free country where you can
say what we like and do what we like.

604
00:47:25,960 --> 00:47:30,498
We choose to sit here and talk as loud as
we like, and if we want to, we shall sing!

605
00:47:30,715 --> 00:47:32,664
As a matter of fact we do want
to sing, don't we?

606
00:47:32,890 --> 00:47:33,973
Yes, we do.

607
00:47:34,413 --> 00:47:37,228
Hoorah, hoorah, hoorah.

608
00:47:37,348 --> 00:47:41,297
???? ???? ???? ????

609
00:47:41,533 --> 00:47:43,600
Hoorah, hoorah, hoorah.

610
00:48:12,194 --> 00:48:14,143
"You, I suppose, are not Mr Pidgeon?"

611
00:48:14,527 --> 00:48:18,169
"Not Mr Pidgeon. Not Mr Pidgeon.
Not Mr Pidgeon Not Mr Pidgeon!"

612
00:48:21,462 --> 00:48:23,533
"Not Mr Pidgeon."

613
00:48:23,947 --> 00:48:29,618
"Not .. Mr .. Pidgeon ..
Not .. Mr .. Pidgeon."

614
00:48:29,962 --> 00:48:37,607
"Not .. Mr .. Pidgeon.
Not .. Mr .. Pidgeon."

615
00:48:38,333 --> 00:48:41,730
Not .. Mr .. Pidgeon.

616
00:48:50,897 --> 00:48:52,667
No. He's certainly not Mr Pidgeon.

617
00:48:53,795 --> 00:48:55,125
Conrad Andersen.

618
00:48:55,453 --> 00:48:58,402
???? ????

619
00:48:59,121 --> 00:49:00,233
Looks genuine.

620
00:49:00,883 --> 00:49:01,759
Yes, Herr Van Dyne.

621
00:49:02,034 --> 00:49:04,171
That's more than can be said for,
you isn't it, Mrs Sorenson?

622
00:49:05,338 --> 00:49:06,671
Oh, I was forgetting.

623
00:49:07,018 --> 00:49:10,070
Your name is not Sorenson.
─ And yours is not Van Dyne.

624
00:49:10,699 --> 00:49:13,497
You are not Danish.
─ And you are not English.

625
00:49:14,504 --> 00:49:16,264
We met once before. You remember?

626
00:49:16,861 --> 00:49:19,527
Who can forget those hands,
that face, that voice?

627
00:49:19,753 --> 00:49:22,861
That whole striking appearance.
─ And my powers of imagination.

628
00:49:23,248 --> 00:49:24,863
Don't forget that.
─ I don't.

629
00:49:25,323 --> 00:49:27,248
No-one knew better how to make
prisoners talk.

630
00:49:27,765 --> 00:49:29,140
Then I don't have to warn you.

631
00:49:29,723 --> 00:49:30,887
But I do have to warn you.

632
00:49:31,007 --> 00:49:33,216
No, no, no. It's no good trying
to bluff me, Miss Clayton.

633
00:49:33,416 --> 00:49:34,890
You said that once before in Düsseldorf.

634
00:49:35,557 --> 00:49:37,031
Next day, I crossed the Dutch frontier.

635
00:49:37,980 --> 00:49:40,656
Ah yes, but this time you haven't
got Mr Pidgeon to help you.

636
00:49:41,013 --> 00:49:42,121
You said that before too.

637
00:49:42,402 --> 00:49:43,929
Well, we shall see when we
bring him here.

638
00:49:44,661 --> 00:49:46,220
From the Army And Navy Club.

639
00:49:47,450 --> 00:49:48,558
Oh, I remember.

640
00:49:48,905 --> 00:49:50,699
You said you wanted to know how
I should look ..

641
00:49:50,819 --> 00:49:53,638
.. tied hand and foot, knowing that the
next day I would face a firing squad.

642
00:49:54,016 --> 00:49:56,917
I should still be interested to know.
─ Oh, you think I'm a coward?

643
00:49:57,481 --> 00:50:00,964
Well, would a coward take a dangerous
post like here, in the midst of the enemy?

644
00:50:01,868 --> 00:50:04,703
Anyway, I'm not a fool.
That's why you're here.

645
00:50:05,915 --> 00:50:08,534
While you and Mr Pidgeon were at
liberty I was in constant danger.

646
00:50:09,164 --> 00:50:12,042
I waited a long time too. Five weeks
wasn't it Miss Lang?

647
00:50:12,326 --> 00:50:13,401
Yes, Herr Van Dyne.

648
00:50:13,878 --> 00:50:16,657
Patience is its own reward, as no doubt
you know from your own job.

649
00:50:17,455 --> 00:50:19,859
By the way, what is your job now?

650
00:50:22,025 --> 00:50:22,918
Oh, well. We'll talk later.

651
00:50:23,187 --> 00:50:26,005
I am quite prepared to meet with this
fellow, the captain of the Danish ship.

652
00:50:26,472 --> 00:50:28,064
We know all about the Helvig,
don't we Lieman?

653
00:50:28,267 --> 00:50:29,364
The Helvig? Yes, Herr Van Dyne.

654
00:50:29,606 --> 00:50:31,837
You were traveling on a neutral ship
to a neutral port.

655
00:50:32,252 --> 00:50:34,193
You were reported this morning
to Contraband Control.

656
00:50:34,611 --> 00:50:37,183
We know about it, don't we Lieman.
─ Yes, Herr Van Dyne, this morning.

657
00:50:37,888 --> 00:50:40,864
You and Mr Pidgeon have been traveling
in neutral ships for the past six months.

658
00:50:41,862 --> 00:50:43,852
This time, you sent your information
through the usual channels.

659
00:50:44,151 --> 00:50:46,783
But you saw how you could save
the Admiralty five days.

660
00:50:48,050 --> 00:50:50,576
Just what is that information,
Mrs Sorenson?

661
00:50:50,980 --> 00:50:53,186
It doesn't occur to you that I've
merely come home?

662
00:50:56,397 --> 00:50:59,552
I know you Mrs Sorenson. I know
people of your kind.

663
00:51:00,238 --> 00:51:03,759
You're not a secret agent who works
for money. You like to do it.

664
00:51:04,399 --> 00:51:07,883
It's in your nature to ask for trouble.
Adventure is in your blood.

665
00:51:09,631 --> 00:51:11,322
Now, you have important information
for the Admiralty.

666
00:51:11,876 --> 00:51:14,593
I know their agents never communicate
with their departments personally.

667
00:51:15,237 --> 00:51:16,608
They do it by code.

668
00:51:17,162 --> 00:51:19,583
Therefore such a coded message
must be in your possession.

669
00:51:21,204 --> 00:51:22,819
Well, where is it?

670
00:51:25,542 --> 00:51:28,640
Nothing is in your notebook. Your
lipstick contains nothing but lipstick.

671
00:51:29,119 --> 00:51:32,067
Your cigarette case contains nothing but
cigarette papers and a made cigarette.

672
00:51:32,443 --> 00:51:34,527
Curious to find a woman who makes
her own cigarettes.

673
00:51:34,745 --> 00:51:36,406
I once met a woman who smoked
a clay pipe.

674
00:51:36,730 --> 00:51:38,365
Really? How interesting.

675
00:51:39,173 --> 00:51:40,933
May I ask you to take off your clothes.

676
00:51:41,985 --> 00:51:43,066
Miss Lang will help you,
won't you Miss Lang?

677
00:51:43,312 --> 00:51:44,780
Yes, Herr Van Dyne.

678
00:51:45,835 --> 00:51:47,093
Well, Mrs Sorenson?

679
00:51:50,903 --> 00:51:52,709
Can I have a cigarette?
─ Certainly.

680
00:51:54,057 --> 00:51:57,203
At our last meeting it was a sign of
surrender when you asked for a cigarette.

681
00:51:58,032 --> 00:52:00,121
May I have one of my own?
─ Of course.

682
00:52:02,341 --> 00:52:04,360
You always did prefer your own
cigarettes, didn't you?

683
00:52:09,470 --> 00:52:10,868
I remember at our last meeting ..

684
00:52:14,015 --> 00:52:16,822
Of course! That's why I couldn't
find anything on you.

685
00:52:17,784 --> 00:52:20,582
I should still like a cigarette.

686
00:53:14,018 --> 00:53:15,708
So that's your job M47.

687
00:53:16,011 --> 00:53:19,354
To find out under what neutral names
German vessels sail across the Atlantic.

688
00:53:20,171 --> 00:53:21,861
Well, we know all about that,
don't we Lieman?

689
00:53:22,415 --> 00:53:23,795
Yes Herr Van Dyne.

690
00:53:25,619 --> 00:53:27,817
All marked with the same special
water-mark.

691
00:53:28,568 --> 00:53:32,549
Well, if the Admiralty wants a message,
why shouldn't they have one. Lieman!

692
00:53:33,225 --> 00:53:35,685
Can you find a neutral ship,
preferably American.

693
00:53:36,117 --> 00:53:38,014
And bound for Europe.
─ Yes, Herr Van Dyne.

694
00:53:38,926 --> 00:53:40,907
We have an excellent one here.

695
00:53:41,027 --> 00:53:43,555
American freighter M.S. Mirabelle.
7000 tons.

696
00:53:43,675 --> 00:53:45,827
Oil-burning cargo machinery
from St Elisabeth.

697
00:53:47,574 --> 00:53:50,006
I think I have to go now Herr Van Dyne.
The cinema will be nearly over.

698
00:53:50,552 --> 00:53:51,960
Go ahead.
─ Goodnight.

699
00:53:52,176 --> 00:53:53,650
Goodnight.

700
00:53:56,913 --> 00:53:58,577
Well, we can leave S.S. Lingham.

701
00:53:58,852 --> 00:54:02,525
But we'll make the Admiralty believe she
sailed under the name of the Mirabelle.

702
00:54:02,910 --> 00:54:05,295
What's the point?
─ Don't you understand?

703
00:54:06,227 --> 00:54:07,727
I bet your Miss Lang understands.

704
00:54:09,532 --> 00:54:12,731
You think there will be trouble if an English
warship arrests this American freighter?

705
00:54:13,098 --> 00:54:16,816
But we are not Germans, who shoot first
and ask questions afterwards.

706
00:54:29,622 --> 00:54:33,227
You will see Miss Clayton, the skipper
of the Mirabelle will get tough.

707
00:54:34,216 --> 00:54:37,803
As the Admiralty have definite information
that the Mirabelle is really a German ship.

708
00:54:38,371 --> 00:54:40,463
The English Command will get tough too.

709
00:54:40,914 --> 00:54:44,356
As the Americans cannot bear anybody
to be tougher than themselves ..

710
00:54:45,580 --> 00:54:48,332
Well .. that's how wars start.

711
00:54:51,745 --> 00:54:57,238
[ national anthem ]

712
00:54:59,348 --> 00:55:02,438
Your National Anthem Mrs Sorenson.
Why don't you stand up?

713
00:55:04,238 --> 00:55:05,555
I see the Captain is already on his feet.

714
00:55:05,801 --> 00:55:07,563
I seem to have missed a good deal.

715
00:55:13,750 --> 00:55:17,919
I have no quarrel with any neutral Captain.
As long as he remains neutral.

716
00:55:18,851 --> 00:55:22,851
Since you got mixed up in this affair,
I must treat you as an enemy.

717
00:55:25,735 --> 00:55:29,651
I realize of course. that up until
now I have been treated as a neutral.

718
00:55:31,031 --> 00:55:34,880
But, with your permission or without, I
intend to rejoin my ship before sunrise.

719
00:55:35,309 --> 00:55:38,313
You're an optimist Captain.
─ And this lady is going with me.

720
00:55:39,187 --> 00:55:41,083
We sail at dawn.
─ Tomorrow?

721
00:55:41,628 --> 00:55:43,393
No .. today.

722
00:55:45,491 --> 00:55:51,988
[ train whistle ]

723
00:56:00,485 --> 00:56:02,578
I'm sorry I dragged you into all this.

724
00:56:03,536 --> 00:56:05,198
You did your best to keep me out of it.

725
00:56:05,623 --> 00:56:07,755
I hope Mr Pidgeon's clever,
otherwise we're sunk.

726
00:56:08,055 --> 00:56:10,356
He doesn't look very clever.
Still, perhaps he is.

727
00:56:11,454 --> 00:56:13,511
After all, you don't look very clever either.

728
00:56:14,085 --> 00:56:15,832
Yet you are.
─ How do you mean?

729
00:56:16,188 --> 00:56:17,982
You both escaped from him before,
didn't you?

730
00:56:18,207 --> 00:56:19,954
Oh, you heard that.
─ Most of it.

731
00:56:20,330 --> 00:56:23,259
And what do you think?
─ Hmm. Skol!

732
00:56:23,968 --> 00:56:25,038
Skol!

733
00:56:26,231 --> 00:56:28,775
Sorry I can't do anything about it.
─ Well, I can.

734
00:56:29,104 --> 00:56:30,625
Yes, I know.
─ Know what?

735
00:56:31,057 --> 00:56:32,775
You stiffened your muscles before
you were tied up.

736
00:56:33,182 --> 00:56:35,379
Good! And what happens now when I relax?

737
00:56:35,679 --> 00:56:36,825
You get a little play in the rope.

738
00:56:37,050 --> 00:56:39,003
And if somebody gives a good hard pull
on the rope?

739
00:56:39,557 --> 00:56:40,712
Who?
─ You.

740
00:56:41,069 --> 00:56:41,811
How?

741
00:56:42,158 --> 00:56:44,975
Haven't you got high heels and long legs?
─ Alright I'm doing it.

742
00:56:45,698 --> 00:56:47,614
What are you waiting for?
─ Brother Grimm.

743
00:56:48,083 --> 00:56:50,421
He must be given another chance
to look at us.

744
00:56:50,618 --> 00:56:53,369
Don't worry about him, he won't come down
again. He can see us from where he is.

745
00:56:53,489 --> 00:56:55,587
How?
─ Can you see the lift door?

746
00:56:56,544 --> 00:56:57,239
No.

747
00:56:57,549 --> 00:56:59,549
Well beside it is mirror which connects
to another one upstairs.

748
00:56:59,840 --> 00:57:01,745
The Gestapo had the same thing in the
prison where I met Van Dyne.

749
00:57:03,639 --> 00:57:06,606
You are clever. Do you think he's
looking at us now?

750
00:57:07,179 --> 00:57:09,432
No, you can always see a flash of
light if anyone is looking at us.

751
00:57:12,540 --> 00:57:14,268
I think I can bring him down.

752
00:57:14,758 --> 00:57:16,702
What for?
─ Never mind.

753
00:57:17,970 --> 00:57:20,073
First we move the chairs a little bit ..
─ Which way?

754
00:57:20,845 --> 00:57:23,108
We want to be just opposite the
door and the mirror.

755
00:57:23,524 --> 00:57:26,291
Pull it to the right .. stop!

756
00:57:26,629 --> 00:57:28,808
He's looking.
─ Now he'll come down.

757
00:57:33,623 --> 00:57:35,153
What did I tell you?

758
00:57:48,393 --> 00:57:50,741
Hello Mr Grimm.
─ Don't call me Grimm!

759
00:57:51,009 --> 00:57:52,887
You were introduced to us
as Grimm, Mr Grimm.

760
00:57:58,718 --> 00:58:00,521
Is that all you came down for Mr Grimm?

761
00:58:07,331 --> 00:58:08,814
You know why he came down?

762
00:58:09,981 --> 00:58:11,352
You want me to say it? Why?

763
00:58:11,727 --> 00:58:14,319
Because after we moved the chairs he
could only see you.

764
00:58:14,788 --> 00:58:15,690
I get you.

765
00:58:16,565 --> 00:58:17,823
Before we start.

766
00:58:18,124 --> 00:58:19,732
We let him have one more look through
his periscope.

767
00:58:20,217 --> 00:58:21,128
How did we get into this place?

768
00:58:21,401 --> 00:58:23,917
Through a door. Iron. I think it was locked.

769
00:58:24,340 --> 00:58:26,691
Along a passage, half bare-boards,
half carpet.

770
00:58:27,206 --> 00:58:29,629
Then, into the lift and down here.
─ More detail?

771
00:58:29,749 --> 00:58:31,216
Can't.
─ Why not?

772
00:58:31,638 --> 00:58:33,263
It was pitch-dark. I had to go where
I was pushed.

773
00:58:33,546 --> 00:58:34,833
Smell anything?
─ Cooking.

774
00:58:34,953 --> 00:58:36,476
Hear anything?
─ Only the cinema.

775
00:58:36,786 --> 00:58:38,579
Close at hand?
─ No, rather muffled.

776
00:58:39,224 --> 00:58:42,443
When they played "God Save The King"
it came from over there.

777
00:58:42,797 --> 00:58:44,126
[ music playing ]

778
00:58:44,451 --> 00:58:47,188
Then what about that?
─ It's not the cinema.

779
00:58:47,658 --> 00:58:48,652
It's a shuffle.

780
00:58:49,784 --> 00:58:51,153
That banjo-player is good.

781
00:58:52,570 --> 00:58:53,867
And the singer.

782
00:58:55,152 --> 00:58:56,318
It must be a nightclub.

783
00:58:57,229 --> 00:59:00,743
So, Van Dyne has his office under
a cinema and a nightclub.

784
00:59:01,844 --> 00:59:03,016
He's having his look.

785
00:59:04,335 --> 00:59:06,363
In two minutes we shall be
looking back at him.

786
00:59:08,302 --> 00:59:09,503
Right, he's gone.

787
00:59:10,514 --> 00:59:13,309
Now I relax ..
─ And I use my legs.

788
00:59:15,012 --> 00:59:17,769
Come on!
─ It's not so easy.

789
00:59:27,019 --> 00:59:28,269
Good girl.

790
00:59:37,097 --> 00:59:39,539
I shouldn't hurt you.
─ Go ahead.

791
00:59:54,876 --> 00:59:55,978
What can you see?

792
00:59:56,618 --> 00:59:58,282
Courts.
─ Nothing else?

793
00:59:59,168 --> 01:00:01,068
No .. just courts.

794
01:00:01,373 --> 01:00:02,889
No sign of Brother Grimm.

795
01:00:06,847 --> 01:00:08,599
Put your hands up .. like they were.

796
01:00:37,381 --> 01:00:38,454
Now then.

797
01:00:40,235 --> 01:00:41,791
Do you trust me?
─ Yes.

798
01:00:42,057 --> 01:00:44,208
We shall catch that last train.
─ And warn Mr Pidgeon.

799
01:00:44,596 --> 01:00:47,116
Yes .. and don't forget to talk
if Grimm is looking.

800
01:01:00,267 --> 01:01:01,646
Look out! He's there again.

801
01:01:03,227 --> 01:01:03,699
Talk!

802
01:01:03,819 --> 01:01:06,032
To be or not to be, that is the
question. Whether it is nobler ..

803
01:01:06,603 --> 01:01:07,125
He's gone!

804
01:01:06,603 --> 01:01:07,253


805
01:01:07,479 --> 01:01:10,245
If he suspects anything, we shall
hear the lift coming down.

806
01:01:15,664 --> 01:01:17,338
No. It's alright.

807
01:01:28,036 --> 01:01:29,621
What are you going to do?
Start at the bottom and work up?

808
01:01:29,965 --> 01:01:32,022
No. Get to the top, and work down.

809
01:01:32,456 --> 01:01:33,765
I've got my fingers crossed.

810
01:01:40,005 --> 01:01:41,481
Bye bye.

811
01:02:10,049 --> 01:02:11,259
Hands up!

812
01:02:15,689 --> 01:02:18,849
Patriotic .. Plaster .. Products.

813
01:02:19,932 --> 01:02:21,803
Very clever Mr Van Dyne.

814
01:04:15,320 --> 01:04:17,672
What do you think you're lighting?
A bonfire?

815
01:04:19,579 --> 01:04:21,623
Why can't you ruddy Wardens mind
your own business?

816
01:04:21,942 --> 01:04:23,936
What do you expect me to light my
pipe with? An electric battery?

817
01:04:24,306 --> 01:04:27,297
Why don't you do something to earn your
3 quid week and leave tax-payers alone?

818
01:04:27,657 --> 01:04:30,305
Poking your long noses into
other people's pockets.

819
01:04:32,264 --> 01:04:33,898
That's all the thanks you'll get.

820
01:04:35,375 --> 01:04:37,924
Hey!
─ Good Lord!

821
01:04:38,265 --> 01:04:40,805
Put out those lights!
─ They must be mad.

822
01:04:41,238 --> 01:04:43,522
Go and see if we can get in that door.

823
01:04:47,910 --> 01:04:49,613
Hoy! .. put out those lights!

824
01:04:50,263 --> 01:04:52,872
Get a crowbar .. we'll have to break in.

825
01:04:53,114 --> 01:04:54,443
Hoy!

826
01:04:56,118 --> 01:04:59,542
Here's the crowbar .. now we're
getting somewhere. Give him room.

827
01:05:03,520 --> 01:05:05,567
No, no, no.

828
01:05:06,098 --> 01:05:08,126
Hoy .. just a minute now.

829
01:05:09,810 --> 01:05:11,769
Put out those lights .. Hoy!
Put out those lights!

830
01:05:12,093 --> 01:05:14,446
Hey, put out those lights!

831
01:05:19,067 --> 01:05:20,475
Hoy!

832
01:05:33,221 --> 01:05:35,304
Ooh!

833
01:05:35,697 --> 01:05:37,430
Oh.

834
01:05:42,785 --> 01:05:44,016
Too bad you didn't catch him Harry.

835
01:05:44,597 --> 01:05:46,250
What's this? German?

836
01:05:46,856 --> 01:05:48,333
Nah .. French.

837
01:05:48,953 --> 01:05:51,276
Commander Andersen.
─ That'll catch him alright.

838
01:05:51,867 --> 01:05:55,814
Taxi! Taxi .. Taxi!

839
01:06:05,750 --> 01:06:06,796
Taxi?
─ Who's next?

840
01:06:07,110 --> 01:06:09,274
Not me .. I'm just in for dinner.

841
01:06:09,501 --> 01:06:10,989
I'll keep it hot for you.
─ What's the name of the street?

842
01:06:11,225 --> 01:06:13,980
Hanover Square. The Three Vikings.
Danish Restaurant.

843
01:06:16,614 --> 01:06:19,360
Foreigner ain't he? Blimey, he's in a state.
What's yours John.

844
01:06:19,656 --> 01:06:21,408
[ door knocking ]

845
01:06:21,969 --> 01:06:23,564
Where's Walter?
─ Gone home.

846
01:06:23,807 --> 01:06:25,155
[ door knocking ]

847
01:06:25,549 --> 01:06:28,877
Better see who the silly fool is,
but be polite. Very polite.

848
01:06:32,545 --> 01:06:33,892
Captain Andersen!

849
01:06:34,207 --> 01:06:35,713
Where's Mr Skold?

850
01:06:36,335 --> 01:06:38,609
Mr Skold, get a map of London.
─ Get a what?

851
01:06:38,729 --> 01:06:40,002
Get a map of London.

852
01:06:40,322 --> 01:06:42,443
What are you waiting for? Get
the Captain a map of London.

853
01:06:43,172 --> 01:06:45,102
I need your help. I need all your help.

854
01:06:45,446 --> 01:06:48,380
You remember the lady who was dining
with me? She's in great danger.

855
01:06:49,079 --> 01:06:50,979
Now listen .. there is going to be a fight.

856
01:06:51,595 --> 01:06:55,885
A big fight! If you're all Danes,
you don't want a reason for fighting.

857
01:06:57,509 --> 01:06:59,458
Who do we fight? Come on.
Here is the map.

858
01:06:59,734 --> 01:07:00,551
And now where do we go?

859
01:07:00,809 --> 01:07:04,028
That's what we have to find out.
I've never seen the place from the outside.

860
01:07:04,300 --> 01:07:05,826
Now you all know London.

861
01:07:06,349 --> 01:07:08,966
Where is their a cinema and a nightclub
in the same building?

862
01:07:10,031 --> 01:07:11,936
The "Garden Of Eden".
The "White Negro".

863
01:07:12,251 --> 01:07:13,293
The Mouse Trap.

864
01:07:13,618 --> 01:07:15,517
There must be a least half
a dozen places ..

865
01:07:16,728 --> 01:07:20,270
Quiet please! Quiet! Quiet!
Where is Chester Square?

866
01:07:20,792 --> 01:07:22,165
Here!

867
01:07:22,736 --> 01:07:24,005
Chester Square.

868
01:07:24,350 --> 01:07:26,777
Now .. steering by the stars ..

869
01:07:27,106 --> 01:07:30,848
We navigated North North-East at an
approximate speed of 8 knots.

870
01:07:31,341 --> 01:07:33,821
We held that course for two and
a half minutes.

871
01:07:34,255 --> 01:07:35,387
That would bring us about here.

872
01:07:36,525 --> 01:07:37,745
Well we all know it isn't there.

873
01:07:38,021 --> 01:07:41,171
At the same speed, we proceeded
due East for another two minutes.

874
01:07:41,378 --> 01:07:43,514
We passed under a big arch.

875
01:07:43,634 --> 01:07:44,579
Admiralty Arch!

876
01:07:45,056 --> 01:07:48,317
Immediately afterwards we altered
course North North-West for 4 minutes.

877
01:07:48,544 --> 01:07:50,736
At a reduced speed.
That would bring us here.

878
01:07:51,182 --> 01:07:51,704
Soho!

879
01:07:51,920 --> 01:07:54,189
Right. So. Now to check it,
we take a cross-bearing.

880
01:07:54,309 --> 01:07:55,135
Give me a pencil.

881
01:07:55,565 --> 01:07:57,278
Where's Hanover Square?

882
01:07:57,879 --> 01:07:58,834
Hanover Square.

883
01:08:01,251 --> 01:08:03,062
Somewhere where these two lines cross.

884
01:08:03,289 --> 01:08:05,690
I say the "Garden Of Eden"
or "The Mouse Trap" or "The White Negro."

885
01:08:06,017 --> 01:08:08,279
But how would you know the right one?
─ Because I know the band.

886
01:08:08,554 --> 01:08:11,163
There is a banjo player and a man who
sings. We have to search until we find it.

887
01:08:11,497 --> 01:08:12,166
Do we all go?

888
01:08:12,383 --> 01:08:14,386
No, no, not all of you.
The five biggest will do.

889
01:08:14,642 --> 01:08:17,708
Well line up, line up. But you can't go
to a nightclub looking like you do.

890
01:08:18,112 --> 01:08:21,853
Yes, somebody has to give me a decent
suit. Somebody about my size. Now then.

891
01:08:25,398 --> 01:08:29,080
You, you, you, you .. and you.

892
01:08:29,686 --> 01:08:32,403
Your suit will do for me,
and don't forget - white ties.

893
01:08:32,758 --> 01:08:35,179
Get me the Army And Navy Club.
─ The Army And Navy Club.

894
01:08:38,405 --> 01:08:39,940
Mr Pidgeon?
─ Who wants him?

895
01:08:40,324 --> 01:08:41,742
The lady is in the cab. Won't come in.

896
01:08:42,382 --> 01:08:44,065
Call Mr Pidgeon!

897
01:08:45,808 --> 01:08:48,751
It's about time she turned up.
He's been like a cat on hot bricks.

898
01:08:49,184 --> 01:08:50,686
What it is to be young.

899
01:08:54,282 --> 01:08:55,562
Where is the lady?
─ In the cab, sir.

900
01:08:56,694 --> 01:08:58,144
Goodnight Bob.
─ Goodnight sir.

901
01:09:03,083 --> 01:09:05,308
Army And Navy Club? He's just
this minute left sir.

902
01:09:06,225 --> 01:09:08,404
Where to, sir?
─ Regency Hotel, Little Row.

903
01:09:09,089 --> 01:09:11,681
What the devil happened to you?
I thought we arranged to meet .. Ahh!

904
01:09:16,162 --> 01:09:17,542
You heard the address.

905
01:09:20,556 --> 01:09:21,861
Mr Pidgeon!

906
01:10:05,203 --> 01:10:07,192
Just a brandy please.
We're not staying long.

907
01:10:34,352 --> 01:10:36,025
That's very nice of you, sir.

908
01:12:17,482 --> 01:12:18,269
Your order, sir?

909
01:12:18,560 --> 01:12:21,603
Tell me, you have no banjo-player?
─ No sir.

910
01:12:22,551 --> 01:12:24,805
Are you sure of that?
─ Yes, sir.

911
01:12:26,926 --> 01:12:28,776
We've never had a banjo-payer gentlemen.

912
01:12:30,805 --> 01:12:31,947
No banjo-player.

913
01:12:32,744 --> 01:12:33,886
Perhaps we can send out
for one for you sir?

914
01:12:34,152 --> 01:12:35,105
Oh no, no.

915
01:12:40,696 --> 01:12:43,437
Tell me .. have you a man singing here?

916
01:12:43,672 --> 01:12:45,841
No sir.
─ No man singing here?

917
01:12:48,159 --> 01:12:51,473
Waiter, haven't you a banjo-payer here?

918
01:12:51,778 --> 01:12:53,038
No sir, I don't think so.

919
01:12:53,274 --> 01:12:54,891
No banjo-player.

920
01:12:56,326 --> 01:13:02,598
[ banjo music ]

921
01:13:03,070 --> 01:13:08,393
[ banjo music ]

922
01:13:09,781 --> 01:13:11,583
I like the banjo-player.

923
01:13:15,048 --> 01:13:18,901
Do you know the muffin-man?
Do you know his name?

924
01:13:19,258 --> 01:13:23,089
Yes I know the muffin-man.
He lives down Drury Lane. Hey!

925
01:13:24,687 --> 01:13:26,218
A marvelous banjo-player.

926
01:13:29,394 --> 01:13:32,755
Do you know the muffin-man?
Do you know his name?

927
01:13:33,046 --> 01:13:36,173
Yes, I know the muffin-man,
he lives down Drury Lane. Hey!!!

928
01:13:39,607 --> 01:13:40,863
I can recommend our cellar.

929
01:13:43,626 --> 01:13:44,705
Oh, but of course.

930
01:13:45,147 --> 01:13:47,400
Everything our cellar contains will
be brought up to your table.

931
01:13:47,626 --> 01:13:49,156
Can't be a very big cellar.

932
01:13:49,614 --> 01:13:51,492
Champagne.
─ At once, sir.

933
01:13:53,793 --> 01:13:55,664
What do you think?

934
01:14:00,940 --> 01:14:02,838
Haven't you a man singing here?
─ No sir, only a girl.

935
01:14:03,044 --> 01:14:03,485
Are you sure?

936
01:14:03,701 --> 01:14:05,429
Very sure sir. We have never
had a man singer.

937
01:14:05,701 --> 01:14:07,147
No man singing here.

938
01:14:07,466 --> 01:14:08,844
You're going sir? You have ordered.

939
01:14:09,150 --> 01:14:11,433
We are no longer interested
in your cellar.

940
01:14:14,528 --> 01:14:16,059
The man!

941
01:14:24,531 --> 01:14:26,441
Of course, it could have been a girl.

942
01:14:42,956 --> 01:14:44,203
Well, why don't you bring the champagne?

943
01:14:44,459 --> 01:14:46,035
At once sir. Waiter. Champagne.,

944
01:14:49,275 --> 01:14:50,928
This is our place alright.

945
01:14:51,635 --> 01:14:53,497
She said she smelled cooking.

946
01:14:58,001 --> 01:15:01,109
From the courtyard into the kitchen,
and from the kitchen into here.

947
01:15:01,769 --> 01:15:03,747
And let me in .. into the cloakroom.

948
01:15:04,013 --> 01:15:06,996
Yes, of course, of course. I think we
should get our coats.

949
01:15:07,229 --> 01:15:09,339
Are we going?
─ No, no.

950
01:15:13,417 --> 01:15:15,698
This is one of the men, behind us.

951
01:15:18,108 --> 01:15:20,384
Is he looking?
─ No.

952
01:15:25,408 --> 01:15:27,985
Watch those two, and don't let
them follow me.

953
01:15:34,265 --> 01:15:35,110
My coat.

954
01:15:36,725 --> 01:15:37,547
That isn't my coat.

955
01:15:37,765 --> 01:15:38,844
57 sir. That was your number.

956
01:15:39,090 --> 01:15:41,630
I can't have that. It's not my coat.
─ It's the coat you gave me, sir.

957
01:15:41,837 --> 01:15:43,796
Are you calling me a liar?
Let me see for myself.

958
01:15:44,137 --> 01:15:44,860
I can't do that sir.

959
01:15:44,980 --> 01:15:46,916
What on earth do you mean? Of course
I can look for my own coat.

960
01:15:47,209 --> 01:15:49,129
What the devil do you think you're doing,
you young whippersnapper?

961
01:15:49,249 --> 01:15:50,030
Let the gentleman look for his coat.

962
01:15:50,241 --> 01:15:51,462
Call the manager!

963
01:15:52,757 --> 01:15:54,450
What a carry on!

964
01:15:57,059 --> 01:15:59,035
Don't let them pass Skold.
─ No Captain.

965
01:16:00,289 --> 01:16:02,909
What's going on? I must get
through please.

966
01:16:03,256 --> 01:16:06,030
Ahhhh!

967
01:16:07,113 --> 01:16:08,629
Ahh!

968
01:16:08,973 --> 01:16:11,199
Come on chaps! Come on.

969
01:16:27,255 --> 01:16:28,171
The paper sir.

970
01:16:28,486 --> 01:16:30,110
Give it to him, any time.

971
01:16:30,917 --> 01:16:32,443
Go on!

972
01:16:32,841 --> 01:16:35,169
Where is the lift? Behind this door?
Answer!

973
01:16:36,471 --> 01:16:37,908
Skold!
─ Yes Captain.

974
01:16:38,237 --> 01:16:39,907
Two men.
─ Yes, Captain.

975
01:17:15,784 --> 01:17:17,251
Do you remember that code?

976
01:17:39,874 --> 01:17:40,884
That door.

977
01:17:48,008 --> 01:17:50,837
Hoorah, hoorah, hoorah!

978
01:18:26,152 --> 01:18:27,530
Perhaps the ground floor?

979
01:18:29,391 --> 01:18:30,410
No.

980
01:18:31,029 --> 01:18:32,860
There must be a secret button for
the basement.

981
01:18:33,097 --> 01:18:34,767
But this is the basement.

982
01:18:37,631 --> 01:18:39,003
How does the lift work?
─ Find out!

983
01:18:39,259 --> 01:18:41,982
What can you do, but press every
single button once.

984
01:18:43,125 --> 01:18:45,979
Except you press every single button
twice! Of course, that's it!

985
01:18:46,254 --> 01:18:47,337
You remember my watch, Skold?

986
01:18:47,669 --> 01:18:49,625
Now, which button would you be sure
not to press twice?

987
01:18:50,024 --> 01:18:51,613
I don't know.
─ The Start button!

988
01:19:07,683 --> 01:19:10,406
Miss Lang? .. Miss Lang?

989
01:19:15,204 --> 01:19:17,204
You always wanted to see me with
my back against the wall.

990
01:19:20,991 --> 01:19:22,540
Drop that gun.

991
01:19:23,927 --> 01:19:25,312
I'm not an amateur, Captain Andersen.

992
01:19:25,622 --> 01:19:26,758
My gun points at Mrs Sorenson.

993
01:19:27,059 --> 01:19:29,134
One single movement.
─ One single movement.

994
01:19:31,303 --> 01:19:32,768
Can we bargain?
─ What will you offer?

995
01:19:33,396 --> 01:19:34,187
Freedom.
─ In return?

996
01:19:34,394 --> 01:19:34,910
Freedom.

997
01:19:35,030 --> 01:19:35,932
What guarantee?
─ My word.

998
01:19:36,052 --> 01:19:38,026
Insufficient.
─ I am not like you Van Dyne.

999
01:19:38,730 --> 01:19:39,828
I use my own name.

1000
01:19:40,382 --> 01:19:42,767
I don't kill people for the crime
 of recognizing me.

1001
01:19:43,347 --> 01:19:44,925
What I do is done by every secret agent.

1002
01:19:45,568 --> 01:19:47,216
You have spies in your
own country, Captain.

1003
01:19:47,761 --> 01:19:49,516
These two .. they use their own names?

1004
01:19:52,702 --> 01:19:54,214
Can we bargain?

1005
01:19:56,636 --> 01:19:58,730
I'll put away my gun if you'll do the same.

1006
01:20:05,241 --> 01:20:08,405
Mrs Sorenson, would you bring in
my coat and hat, please.

1007
01:20:09,832 --> 01:20:11,813
The Police are here. I've got your coat.

1008
01:20:13,731 --> 01:20:15,684
Well, what are you waiting for? Go on.

1009
01:20:20,267 --> 01:20:23,741
I give you my word .. that as
soon as we step out of the lift ..

1010
01:20:24,205 --> 01:20:26,486
You are free to go where you like.

1011
01:20:28,092 --> 01:20:29,557
I hope we shall never meet again.

1012
01:20:30,843 --> 01:20:32,214
I hope so for your sake Captain.

1013
01:20:32,552 --> 01:20:34,627
I've no intention of visiting Germany.

1014
01:20:38,738 --> 01:20:40,428
You timed that very nicely Captain.

1015
01:20:41,283 --> 01:20:42,588
The Police are here.

1016
01:20:43,078 --> 01:20:44,352
Meet me at Victoria at 3:30.

1017
01:20:44,578 --> 01:20:46,527
Yes Captain. I locked them in.

1018
01:20:47,501 --> 01:20:48,627
Are you alright?

1019
01:20:54,205 --> 01:20:55,979
We haven't got much time.
─ And I've got to go to the Admiralty.

1020
01:20:56,215 --> 01:20:58,148
I know. We'll meet you at Victoria.

1021
01:20:59,125 --> 01:21:00,618
The window. Over there.

1022
01:21:21,920 --> 01:21:23,704
Careful. One step at a time.

1023
01:21:23,920 --> 01:21:26,697
Aren't you running with them?
─ No. I'll show you the way first.

1024
01:21:36,806 --> 01:21:37,980
Stop!

1025
01:21:40,252 --> 01:21:43,826
The lift is coming. Stay where you are.
Don't move.

1026
01:21:59,573 --> 01:22:01,621
Who's there?
─ Hello Van Dyne.

1027
01:22:02,030 --> 01:22:03,698
You didn't escape?
─ You innocent!

1028
01:22:04,171 --> 01:22:05,559
Well, your Police didn't get me anyway.

1029
01:22:05,795 --> 01:22:07,911
No wonder you hoped we'd
never meet again.

1030
01:22:58,559 --> 01:22:59,937
Van Dyne?

1031
01:23:07,690 --> 01:23:09,540
He always said he was tough.

1032
01:23:26,233 --> 01:23:30,820
Well .. thank you for everything Erik.
And goodbye.

1033
01:23:31,687 --> 01:23:32,403
Goodbye.

1034
01:23:33,074 --> 01:23:33,830
Thank you all.

1035
01:23:34,243 --> 01:23:38,102
Luke .. Henry .. Bjorn .. Vorsbald .. Arnold.

1036
01:23:38,318 --> 01:23:40,026
Thank you Arnold .. and goodbye.

1037
01:23:40,261 --> 01:23:41,099
Goodbye.

1038
01:23:41,381 --> 01:23:42,768
Goodbye.

1039
01:23:51,613 --> 01:23:52,932
Now she's missed the train.

1040
01:23:53,208 --> 01:23:55,511
Pidgeon. You don't know that girl at all.

1041
01:24:04,583 --> 01:24:05,527
Done it?

1042
01:24:05,997 --> 01:24:07,189
Yes.

1043
01:24:33,834 --> 01:24:36,137
Here are your papers Captain,
and here's your clearance paper.

1044
01:24:36,551 --> 01:24:38,244
You can heave up anchor
whenever you like.

1045
01:24:40,175 --> 01:24:41,828
Skold! Heave up!

1046
01:24:42,670 --> 01:24:44,866
You should hoist this code signal to
avoid being stopped again.

1047
01:24:45,734 --> 01:24:48,222
Well, Captain, next time I hope you make
up for the dinner you missed.

1048
01:24:48,508 --> 01:24:50,231
Thank you Lieutenant-Commander Ashton
and goodbye.

1049
01:24:50,659 --> 01:24:54,029
Oh, and uh .. here's a little something
for your stomach-ache.

1050
01:25:15,139 --> 01:25:17,619
Mrs Sorenson .. the Captain wants
to see you in his cabin.

1051
01:25:18,269 --> 01:25:19,413
Thank you.

1052
01:25:30,281 --> 01:25:31,729
That girl certainly likes trouble.

1053
01:25:41,560 --> 01:25:42,875
Come in Mrs Sorenson.

1054
01:25:46,016 --> 01:25:47,305
You wanted to see me Captain?

1055
01:25:48,132 --> 01:25:49,530
Sit down Mrs Sorenson.

1056
01:26:00,689 --> 01:26:01,919
Mrs Sorenson, because of you ..

1057
01:26:02,214 --> 01:26:06,251
The whole Control Port thinks I'm an
old woman suffering from indigestion.

1058
01:26:07,320 --> 01:26:09,929
It's lucky that nobody knew what
nonsense I was up to.

1059
01:26:10,204 --> 01:26:13,315
You think our Police and Intelligence
departments are pretty dumb, don't you?

1060
01:26:13,856 --> 01:26:15,303
Open your stomach-powder.

1061
01:26:32,051 --> 01:26:33,534
And nobody knew.

1062
01:26:35,188 --> 01:26:41,790
[ watch chimes ]

1063
01:26:50,747 --> 01:26:52,991
I have had enough trouble because of you.

1064
01:26:53,710 --> 01:26:55,492
And I feel I shall have more.

1065
01:26:59,201 --> 01:27:00,923
Drop that life-jacket ..

1066
01:27:14,353 --> 01:27:18,851
Hoorah .. hoorah .. hoorah.

1067
01:27:35,164 --> 01:27:39,041
Subs for KG
by "Targa".
